{{Merge|Karipúna French Creole language|date=November 2017}}
{{Infobox language |name=Lanc-Patuá |altname=Amapá French Creole |states=[[Brazil]] (in the state of [[Amapá]]) |speakers=2,400 |date=2008 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Creole |fam1=[[French-based creole languages|French Creole]] |fam2=French Guianese Creole |iso3=kmv |glotto=kari1301 |glottorefname=Karipuna Creole French |lingua=51-AAC-cdd }}
'''Lanc-Patuá''' is a [[creole language]] spoken in the state of [[Amapá]] in [[Brazil]], primarily now around the capital, [[Macapá]]. It is a [[French-based creole language]], spoken by local Indians and immigrants from [[French Guiana]], the [[Caribbean]] and other areas of Brazil, and their descendants. It has some [[English language|English]] and [[Brazilian Portuguese|Portuguese]] influence on its vocabulary, but its grammar is clearly similar to the [[French-based creole languages]] of the Caribbean and the [[Indian Ocean]].
Lanc-Patuá is derived from '''Karipúna Creole''' spoken by indigenous Amerindians. The [[substratum]] language of Karipúna Creole was the now-extinct Tupian language [[Karipuna language (Amapá)|Karipúna]]. The name comes from the French ''Langue Patois'', meaning simply dialectal language.
Lanc-Patuá creole typically refers to what is spoken in [[Macapá]], the capital of [[Amapá]] state, whereas Amapá French creole refers to the French-lexified creoles in the Uaça [[Indian Reservation]]: Karipúna French creole (KFC) and Galibi-Marwono French creole (GMFC).{{Citation needed|date=December 2016}}
==History== In Brazil, there are two Creolophone groups that speaks two creole languages: one [[French language|French]]-lexifed and the other Portuguese-lexifed. The Portuguese-lexicon creole is spoken in the state of [[São Paulo]], while the French-lexified creole is spoken in the state of [[Amapá]] in North Eastern Brazil, the Brazilian state bordering [[French Guiana]].
Lanc-Patuá is said to be spoken by descendants of [[French Guiana]] and [[French-based creole languages|French Creole]]-speaking immigrants from the [[French Antilles]] who number approximately 25,000. The southern variety, Lanc-Patúa, shows some English influence because of a relatively large number of migrants from [[St. Lucia]] and [[Dominica]]. It is a variety of the [[French Guianese Creole]].
==See also== * [[French Guianese Creole]] * [[Antillean creole]] * [[Karipúna French Creole language|Karipúna French Creole]]
